# 7. 開幕

Tsukasa: The day has finally arrived.
Rui: Yes, it has. Please allow me to take this opportunity to thank you all again for helping me with this.
Rui: Especially since the actors' workshop was running in parallel. Practicing for both couldn't have been easy.
Nene: I mean, we knew that things would be hard going in...
Tsukasa: She's right! Plus, we've been wanting to put the things we learned during this workshop into practice!
Emu: I'm so excited to have everyone see this show!
Rui: Me too. This will be the culmination of everything we learned during this workshop.
Rui: The audience consists only of the workshop's teachers and participants. They'll be giving us their harsh assessments once we're done.
Rui: But let's forget about all that for now. We just need to do what we always do.
Rui: Put on the best show we can for the audience that's right in front of us.
Emu: Right!
Tsukasa: I believe we're all eager to hear how this show is received, as well.
Nene: It is pretty different from the ones we normally do.
Emu: I wasn't sure we'd be able to pull it off, but I'm really excited to perform it now!
Rui: Hehe. As the director, that makes me very happy to hear.
Tsukasa: Your script and directing plan are both very you, but there are twists, as well.
Tsukasa: We know you struggled quite a lot with this... But this is the answer you arrived upon.
Rui: It is. I've put everything I can currently bring to bear into it.
Tsukasa: Alright. Let's go show them how our director, and Wonderlands×Showtime, break new ground.
Tsukasa: We're going to make this the best show ever.
Emu, Rui & Nene: Yeah! Yes.
Sakaki: “Next, we have... Ah, Kamishiro.”
Sakaki: “Speaking of which, Tom, didn't you have a talk with him the other day?”
Tom: <“Yes, I just gave him a small piece of advice. I believe that young man has quite a lot of potential.”>
Sakaki: “Oh? And that's not just lip service, is it?”
Tom: <“Of course not. I think you'll understand soon enough.”>
Sakaki: Alright, I guess it's okay for me to get my hopes up a little.
Carriage Driver: “Eep...! H-Help me...!!”
???: “Hahaha! Crying for help already?”
Monster: “I know you can run faster than that. You do not want to bore me!”
Carriage Driver: “Wh-What...?! Th-The monster's on top of the carriage...!”
Monster: “Right down the embankment, huh? That means I win our game of tag.”
Monster: “*Sigh* How dull. Just when I thought you would help me pass the time...”
Monster: “I know! I could masquerade as a human in the city.”
Monster: “I may yet find something more interesting.”
Tavernkeeper: “Alright, here's your ale. Haven't seen you around here before, son. Are you a traveler?”
Young Traveler?: “Yes, more or less!”
Tavernkeeper: “Then, be careful. They say that there's a fearsome monster lurking in the woods nearby.”
Young Traveler?: “Oh...? What's so fearsome about it?”
Tavernkeeper: “It's a ruthless thing, and make no mistake. I've heard that it's smarter, stronger and faster than any human out there, and it's a cruel and selfish beast.”
Tavernkeeper: “Even today, I heard that it chased around a horse-drawn carriage just for fun. The poor driver was scared half to death.”
Young Traveler?: “I see. It sounds like it wanted someone to play with.”
Tavernkeeper: “That's no excuse to chase people around! Anyway, just be careful out there.”
Monster: “As I suspected, humans just don't understand.”
Monster: “What else could be more important in this world than having as much fun as possible?”
Monster: “*Sigh* I'm getting bored of this 'tavern' place already... Hm?”
???: “♪—————— ♪——————~~”
Monster: “What is this...?”
Minstrel: “Oh, is this the first time you've ever heard a wandering minstrel sing?”
Monster: “A wandering minstrel...?”
Minstrel: “That's right! My friends and I travel around to various parts, singing about that region's local legends and history.”
Monster: “Hey, that sounds like fun...!”
Monster: “That song made me completely forget how bored I was.”
Monster: “Which means, if I can learn to sing like a minstrel, then...”
Monster: “Hey! You must teach me how to sing!”
Minstrel: “What? Does that mean you wanna become my apprentice?!”
Minstrel: “My own apprentice...! I've always wanted one... No, if I'm going to be your master, then I have to act more dignified. Ahem!”
Minstrel: “Do you really want to become my apprentice?”
Monster: “Your apprentice...? Yes, if it means learning how to sing like that.”
Monster: “Please, make me your apprentice!”
Minstrel: “Hmm... I can't really turn you away after seeing that look on your face...”
Minstrel: “It's settled, then. Starting today, you'll call me your master.”
Monster: “Yes, of course!”
Monster: “♪—————— ♪——————”
Minstrel: “Hey, you're better than I was expecting.”
Minstrel: “But don't you know any less bizarre verses? These sound like something right out of a drunkard's nightmare.”
Monster: “Then, what words should I sing instead?”
Minstrel: “Well, something that resonates with everyone's hearts! For example...”
Local Human A: “Young man, you're that minstrel's apprentice, yes? Can you sing a song for me?”
Monster: “I refuse. I'm not learning how to sing for the likes of you.”
Minstrel: “Hey, how many times do I have to tell you not to talk to people like that?!”
Minstrel: “Also, it's a minstrel's job to sing and tell stories to people. If you can't accept that, then I won't teach you any more.”
Monster: “Ah, that would be a problem... Alright, just one song.”
Monster: “♪———— ♪——————”
Local Human A: “Oh, this is...”
Local Human B: “Really good! I could listen to him sing all day.”
Monster: “Oh, I guess some humans do have good taste...”
Local Human A: “Thank you, young man! I feel ready to do my best at work again tomorrow.”
Monster: “Sure! I might even be willing to sing for you again sometime.”
Local Human A: “Really? Then, I think I'll bring my wife along next time.”
Minstrel: “Hehe...”
Tsukasa: (And so, the monster begins to blend in amongst the humans.)
Tsukasa: (This all began with his simple quest to seek “fun”, but...)
Minstrel: “You have a way of making everybody around you smile.”
Minstrel: “Every now and then, you do something way off-beat... But I know it's all in good fun.”
Minstrel: “I couldn't have asked for a better apprentice.”
Rui: (The monster's nature hasn't actually changed. He's a simple creature who only wishes to have fun.)
Rui: (But...)
Tsukasa: (Something begins to blossom within his heart.)
Tsukasa: (He hasn't realized it yet, but a compulsion to express these feelings is slowly growing...)
Monster: “Thank you...”
ArcLand Director A: That was good.
ArcLand Director B: Yes, it was a subdued performance, but the lights and the way he used the stage made it an impactful scene.
Emu: (In big theatres, you have to really exaggerate your movements to make sure everyone in the audience can see what you're doing.)
Emu: (But Tsukasa and Rui came up with the best way to use this stage after some really long practices and discussions.)
Tsukasa: (Things have gone well so far, but the hard part is coming up...)
Tsukasa: (One day, a lone hunter arrives in the city where the monster lives, and everything changes...)
Hunter: “You must all listen to me. There is a horrible monster living among you in this very city.”
Local Humans: “I-In this city...?”
Hunter: “It's transformed into a human and is currently masquerading around as one of you. However, its true nature is fundamentally inhuman.”
Hunter: “This creature is selfish, pleasure-seeking, and thoughtlessly cruel. That's what makes it a monster.”
Hunter: “Before it inevitably harms someone... I must expose it, and put it down.”
Local Humans: “That's terrifying...”
Local Humans: “Yeah, and it's pretending to be human like us? How creepy.”
Minstrel: “I don't like this mood in the square...”
Monster: “Me neither...”
